Nearly 3 months later and this video now has over half a million views. This has all been a pleasant surprise for me which I can't thank you guys enough for.

However, accompanying the feeling of thanks is the feeling of guilt. I really do hope this little project of mine won't stop Jack Stauber from making his own original video for Buttercup, if he had planned to do so in the first place. Truthfully, the reason why this video is as popular as it is now is because the timing of its upload perfectly coincided with Stauber's significant boosts in popularity. Being the multi-talented artist that he is, the existence of this already-popular video may have lost him a chance to create his own rendition for a Buttercup video.

So I do hope most of the praise that goes toward this video goes to him as well. Let's not forget of course the talents of Masaaki Yuasa and company, the brilliant minds behind the animation used in this video, KICK-HEART. The only praise I personally should be receiving is my combination of these two already-wonderful elements into a single item.

Thank you for reading.

As western music is illegal in Iran, in 1998 I smuggled Garage inc album cassette in a loose tea box from Dubai to Shiraz, Iran. I was 20 years old fanatic Metallica fan. Deprived from buying their albums or going to their concerts in my country. I had a Sony Sport Walkman. Used to hide it in my jacket sleeve and hide the headphones under my wooly hat. Walking up and down Cinema Saadi Street, listening to my heros. Two years later I immigrated to the UK and went to 3 live show, including the one that lars missed and joe played the drums.
This song had no right to go as hard as it did in 1983. Still an absolute banger in 2024.
Tesla, Whitesnake, Cinderella,  Great White, Metallica, Ozzy, Bon Jovi, Guns and Roses...etc. We were spoiled if you rocked to these group's from 1985 to 1995. 10 years of epically great rock.
Lit was lit before lit was even lit.

80s music TOTALLY ROCKED!!!! I'm so incredibly thankful that I grew up as a teen in that decade. The perfect time to be in the teen years. Back then we had to go to an arcade to play video games. We had drive in theatres and stone washed blue jeans. No internet, instead we actually had real friends who liked to do crazy things to have fun. Friday and Saturday nights we even went to the skating rinks. Oh it was so much fun, especially when you eyed that pretty girl you were scared to talk to. No we didn't text back then, there were no smart phones or cell phones. Back then you actually called a girl, if you had the nerve, and asked her out on a date. To top it all off the movies were great and so was TV back when everyone was always trying figure out what JR Ewing was up to on Dallas. We only got to see cartoons on Saturday morning, then after that we played outside all day trying to find an old tire to push down the hill to see it bounce. We played outside all the time. A wonderful time to be a kid, especially when you finally heard your favorite song from Casey Casem top 40 on the radio. If you were focused, you would record the song from the radio onto a tape recorder, LOL!!!
Who else agrees with me that AIC should be in the rock & roll Hall of fame?

songs.post_title: 47 Songs about Overcoming Obstacles, Adversity, Hard Times, Challenges and Not Giving Up
songs.comment_text:
When I was 16, after 10 years of compulsory public education, I watched a couple of friends leave to further their tertiary educations overseas, while I could only get a local polytechnic diploma. 2-3 years after that, I watch more friends walk proudly into various local universities, while my educational journey came to an end. I came from a poor family and my father could only send me for basic education and nothing more as I had 3 younger siblings who were still schooling. After 3 years in the military, I began working and became the family bread winner. I never stopped working for almost 25 years and slowly climbed up the career ladder. A few years ago, I hear this song and it struck a cord in me. I decided it was time. I enrolled in graduate school at 45. Next to the lecturer, I was the oldest person in class. Everywhere I went on campus, I stood out like a sore thumb. Everyone was on laptops and tablets, while I was on books, papers and pencils. But I didn't give up, I kept turning to this song to keep me going. THIS was MY fight song. I struggled hard but help soon came. Classmates half my age who once spurred the 'old dude' from groups in class, turned to me for life advice and in turn, helped me navigate the digital world and gadgets and online submissions. I still turned to this song to keep the fire going when I wanted to give up.

I graduated last year, ahead of schedule, 4 years out of a 5 year part time degree programme. My parents couldn't make it as they were too frail. There was no one in the audience clapping for a 49 year old graduate. But I was proud. I had made it. And this song was one of those songs that just kept me telling myself ... I can do this!

songs.comment_text: This song opens the most depressing moment of my life. One time in the past, I tried to leave this beautiful world in a way that was against my faith. I smiled at the people around me but deep inside I was asking for help. The attempts failed and things got better because of God and of my mom. Now I am a registered nurse helping patients and trying to help those who are risks for suicide. Thank you Alexander for this wonderful song.
